{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5576907-f3bd-4f37-88f8-85dccc74eac6","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and launches your server automatically.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (e.g., using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package with `stdio` transport).\n- Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout, to avoid corrupting the protocol stream.\n\nIf you've already published/built the server, you can point directly at the DLL instead:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"dotnet\",\n\"args\": [\"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"29004a42-5864-4381-9f7b-3eb6fc65a460","outputTokens":342,"requestId":"7FCD:5278E:45D7912:4C6804C:69F15AFC"},"id":"e26bc7ad-98f7-442f-8d41-ab6695e3d4ab","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:12:37.570Z","parentId":"b5d16023-c060-455d-9222-f2a965edf727"}
